When it came to raising the children after the divorce, women expected to take care of them, while men would pay child support.

Children were seen as being weaker than men, and therefore the responsibility of the women.

Most women indicated that providing an education was too expensive and irrelevant for their daughters, while for their sons, it was the priority.

“Saying what you are going to do is not enough; you have to show what you could do.”

The programme launched in Ivory Coast on the basis of a pilot study to provide free psycho-social support to women facing intimate partner violence.

University partners decided to establish a school-club partnership to test training needs and the effectiveness of school-based support groups in improving the access to contraception among schoolgirls.

On leaving the camp in the Kasai region, the victims sought sanctuary in the Tanganyika Province.

Around 29% did not have access to an institutional service, and many were living in camps for internally displaced people (IDP) with poor family planning services.

Many were young women from families displaced by the brutal, systematic “death squad” attacks in the Kasai region, with their husbands either killed during the violence or returning with mental health problems.
